{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473770"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:14:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:14:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2749"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2749"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.88,0.01,0.04,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2749"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112208"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2749","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2749"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2749"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94273"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1560"},{"type":"tags","id":"2982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11471"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3604"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44096"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112208"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-month-old boy is brought by his mother to the General Practice clinic for his routine health check. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. The pregnancy and birth were uncomplicated. His mother reports that he has met his gross motor milestones but has been slower with language development. He occasionally repeats words he hears but uses few words consistently.  He has had his hearing and vision screened recently as part of a free screening program in a shopping centre. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. When offered toys, he shows limited interest in interactive play. His mother mentions that he often seems to be in his own world and is happy to play trains for at least one hour alone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autism spectrum disorder","Intellectual disability","Mixed receptive-expressive language disorder","Social (pragmatic) communication disorder","Childhood-onset fluency disorder"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child exhibits several features consistent with autism spectrum disorder, though presented more subtly in the clinical scenario. The key features include delayed language development, limited social interaction, and being \u0027lost in his own world\u0027 with repetitive play. While a formal diagnostic evaluation would be required to confirm the diagnosis, \u003Cstrong\u003Eautism spectrum disorder\u003C/strong\u003E should be strongly suspected based on this presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntellectual disability\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential differential diagnosis, as cognitive delays can lead to some similar symptoms such as speech delay and atypical play. However, the repetitive behaviors and social communication deficits are more suggestive of ASD. Intellectual disability can also co-occur with ASD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed receptive-expressive language disorder\u003C/strong\u003E could explain the speech delay, but would not account for the restricted interests, repetitive behaviors, and poor social engagement seen in this child. \u003Cstrong\u003ESocial (pragmatic) communication disorder\u003C/strong\u003E is characterized by difficulties with social use of language, but does not involve restricted interests or repetitive behaviors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChildhood-onset fluency disorder\u003C/strong\u003E (stuttering) presents with disruptions in fluency of speech, which is not described in this case. The speech abnormalities here (limited consistent word use with some echolalia) are more consistent with ASD.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Consider autism spectrum disorder in children with atypical social interaction patterns and repetitive behaviours.","Intellectual disability and specific learning disorders can co-occur with autism spectrum disorder and should be considered in the differential diagnosis.","Delayed language development with echolalia can be an early sign of autism spectrum disorder."],"references":["Soto T, Kiss IG, Carter AS. SYMPTOM PRESENTATIONS AND CLASSIFICATION OF AUTISM SPECTRUM DISORDER IN EARLY CHILDHOOD: APPLICATION TO THE\u00a0DIAGNOSTIC CLASSIFICATION OF MENTAL HEALTH AND DEVELOPMENTAL DISORDERS OF INFANCY AND EARLY CHILDHOOD (DC:0\u20135). Infant Meant Health J. 2018; 37(5): 486-97.","Guidelines for preventiative activities in general practice 10th Edition: Developmental Delay and Autism [Internet]. Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. 2025 Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/development-and-behaviour/autism"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94273"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2749"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94273","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94273"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-26T18:08:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-26T18:08:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2749"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112208"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udfad","name":"Psychiatry","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:46+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"descr